snippet.textDisplay: I think why a lot of people hate the look of dreadlocks is because essentially it's just matted hair. Afro hair gets matted/tangled more easily, because the cuticles are more open so they lock into eachother more easily. In straight hair the cuticles are basically closed, so to get it matted naturally, you have to neglect it for a long time. That's why a lot of people see it as dirty and unkempt.

It’s not gonna blend properly bc your hair isn’t the same texture as braiding hair AND it’s too heavy for your scalp. Which is why their hair tends to fall out so much when they do it.

Like just factually white peoples must wash their hair more often to keep it clean and healthy. And if you mat your hair and don’t loc it properly EVEN IF WASHED it won’t be right because it won’t dry all the way through and you can get mold


You can “it’s just hair” all you want but it’s just hair that’s gonna be proper damaged if you don’t do good things for it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Saw the debate in a few comments and I asked my friend about vikings wearing dreads because he studies vikings in depth. He said that yeah, a portion of them probably did. Vikings were a mash up of a bunch of various cultures. They weren't just a single thing. So...yes, white people have had dreads in the past. I KNOW they weren't called dreads but I don't know what we would call them now other than that. I don't think all or even most white people with the style are meaning to culturally appropriate from African Americans with this fact being stated. I have viking ancestors. I wouldn't be appropriating anything.

Having said that, it doesn't look that great on us most of the time. Yikes.

Also box braids are a completely different topic and I often see vikings as an excuse for white people wearing those. They did not. They had braids but not box braids.
